04468nam a22006735i 9781477316207DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20212018txu    fo  d z      eng d  a2017056778  a97814773162077 a10.7560/3161842doi  a(DE-B1597)588348  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX00aPQ7081b.D483 2018 4aPQ7081b.D483 2018 7aLIT0041002bisacsh04a860.9/9809042231 aDi Stefano, Eugenio Claudio, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Vanishing Frame :bLatin American Culture and Theory in the Postdictatorial Era /cEugenio Claudio Di Stefano. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2018  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tINTRODUCTION Freedom at the End of the Postdictatorial Era -- tPART 1 POSTDICTATORIAL AESTHETICS -- tCHAPTER 1 From Revolution to Human Rights -- tCHAPTER 2 Disability and Redemocratization -- tCHAPTER 3 Making Neoliberal History -- tPART 2 TOWARD A POLITICS OF THE FRAME -- tCHAPTER 4 The Reappearance of the Frame -- tCHAPTER 4 The Reappearance of the Frame -- tCHAPTER 6 Literary Form Now -- tCODA The Victim, the Frame -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the postdictatorial era, Latin American cultural production and criticism have been defined by a series of assumptions about politics and art—expecially the claim that political freedom can be achieved by promoting a more direct experience between the textual subject (often a victim) and the reader by eliminating the division between art and life. The Vanishing Frame argues against this conception of freedom, demonstrating how it is based on a politics of human rights complicit with economic injustices. Presenting a provocative counternarrative, Eugenio Claudio Di Stefano examines literary, visual, and interdisciplinary artists who insist on the autonomy of the work of art in order to think beyond the politics of human rights and neoliberalism in Latin American theory and culture. Di Stefano demonstrates that while artists such as Diamela Eltit, Ariel Dorfman, and Albertina Carri develop a concept of justice premised on recognizing victims’ experiences of torture or disappearance, they also ignore the injustice of economic inequality and exploitation. By examining how artists such as Roberto Bolaño, Alejandro Zambra, and Fernando Botero not only reject an aesthetics of experience (and the politics it entails) but also insist on the work of art as a point of departure for an anticapitalist politics, this new reading of Latin American cultural production offers an alternative understanding of recent developments in Latin American aesthetics and politics that puts art at its center and the postdictatorship at its end.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aChilean literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aDictatorshipzLatin AmericaxHistoryy20th century. 0aPolitics and literaturezLatin Americay20th century. 0aSpanish American literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Caribbean & Latin American.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/31618440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477316207423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477316207/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK